{{other uses|Tintamarre (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox recurring event | name = Tintamarre | image = Tintamarre Fredericton 2010.jpg | caption = Tintamarre noisemakers in [[Fredericton]], [[New Brunswick]] in 2010 | status = Active | genre = Traditional | frequency = Annually and/or at gatherings of [[Acadians]] | location = [[Acadia]] | country = Primarily [[Canada]] | years_active = 1955–present | founded = {{Start date|1955|08|10|df=y}} | founder_name = Norbert Robichaud }} '''''Tintamarre''''' is an [[Acadia]]n tradition of marching through one's community making noise with improvised [[Musical instrument|instruments]] and other [[wikt:noisemaker|noisemakers]], usually in celebration of [[National Acadian Day]]. The term originates from the [[Acadian French]] word meaning "clangour" or "din". The practice is intended to demonstrate the vitality and solidarity of Acadian society, and to remind others of the presence of [[Acadians]]. It originated in the mid-twentieth century, likely inspired by an ancient French folk custom.<ref name=encyclopedia>{{cite web|url=http://www.ameriquefrancaise.org/en/article-319/Tintamarre:__a_New_Acadian_%E2%80%9CTradition%E2%80%9D__.html|title=Tintamarre: a New Acadian "Tradition"|author=Labelle, Ronald|date=|work=Encyclopedia of French Cultural Heritage in North America|publisher=|accessdate=September 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ol7ozG8Q?url=http://www.ameriquefrancaise.org/en/article-319/Tintamarre%3A__a_New_Acadian_%E2%80%9CTradition%E2%80%9D__.html#|archivedate=2014-04-11|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Acadians gather in Caraquet to mark Tintamarre |author=Nabuurs, Jody |newspaper=[[Telegraph-Journal]] |date=August 16, 2010 |url=http://telegraphjournal.canadaeast.com/rss/article/1177445 |accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref>
==History== Tintamarre is a recent tradition established by people of Acadian descent in Canada in the mid-20th century, although it is believed to have been inspired by the ancient [[France|French]] folk custom of ''[[Charivari]]''.<ref name=encyclopedia/> In 1955, during the commemorations of the 200th anniversary of the [[Expulsion of the Acadians]], the Archbishop of [[Moncton]], Norbert Robichaud, circulated an instruction sheet for the marking of the event. He advised families to kneel in outdoor prayer once the [[church bell]]s began to ring, and he wrote:
{{quote|''Une fois la prière terminée, on fera pendant plusieurs minutes, un joyeux tintamarre de tout ce qui peut crier, sonner et faire du bruit: sifflets de moulin, klaxons d'automobiles, clochettes de bicyclettes, criards, jouets, etc.'' ("Once the prayer is finished, there will be a joyful tintamarre lasting for several minutes, featuring anything, everything and everyone that can make noise, shout and ring: mill whistles, car horns, bicycle bells, squawking objects, toys, etc.")<ref name=cyber>{{cite web|url=http://cyberacadie.com/index.php?/coutumes/Le-Tintamarre.html|title=Le Tintamarre|author=|date=|work=Cyber Acadie|publisher=|accessdate=September 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ol805fj5?url=http://cyberacadie.com/index.php?%2Fcoutumes%2FLe-Tintamarre.html#|archivedate=2014-04-11|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>}}
[[René Lévesque]], a [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|Radio-Canada]] journalist was in Moncton covering the commemoration of the Acadian deportation, and described the ''tintamarre'' in his report:
{{quote|''Écoutez encore, c'est la vie de l'Acadie française en 1955, deux siècles après la mort qu'on prévoyait.'' ("Listen! It is the sound of the heartbeat of French-speaking Acadia in 1955 - two centuries after it was supposed to have been extinguished.")<ref name=encyclopedia/>}}
In 1979, the ''Société Nationale des Acadiens'' sought to revive the Tintamarre for the celebrations in [[Caraquet, New Brunswick]] of the 375th anniversary of the founding of Acadia.<ref name=cyber/> Organizers urged celebrants to reaffirm their Acadian identity loudly and clearly, so as to emphasize the slogan of the celebrations: ''On est venus c'est pour rester'' ("We've come back and we're here to stay"). In 1980, although there were no official efforts to organize any noisemaking, spontaneous Tintamarres were reported in Caraquet and in other Acadian communities in New Brunswick. By 1984, area newspapers noted discussions of holding "traditional Tintamarres" to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the [[Flag of Acadia]], even though the "tradition" was only a few decades old.<ref name=encyclopedia/>
The Tintamarre held during the 2009 ''Festival acadien'' in Caraquet involved 40,000 participants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://festivalacadien.ca/en/history|title=History|publisher=Festival acadien de Caraquet|accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OlDzT9hV?url=http://festivalacadien.ca/en/history#|archivedate=2014-04-11|quote=The 2009 Tintamarre, which drew 40,000 participants, will forever be remembered as the largest gathering of its type in Acadian history!|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>
==Acadian symbol== [[File:Tintamarre during National Acadian Day 2009, Caraquet New Brunswick.jpg|thumb|The Tintamarre in [[Caraquet, New Brunswick]] in 2009]] Along with the Acadian flag and the hymn ''[[Ave Maris Stella]]'', the Tintamarre has become widely recognized as an Acadian symbol. It has become an important part of National Acadian Day celebrations in Canada and of any other events affirming Acadian identity and accomplishments. In 2006, a Tintamarre was held to help inaugurate a new medical training program at the [[Université de Moncton]]; when asked why noisemaking had been included in an academic event, organizers explained that the Tintamarre was "an essential Acadian custom".<ref name=encyclopedia/><ref name=cyber/><ref>{{cite news |title=Joyful hullaballoo greets visitors to Acadian festival |author=Hanlon, Michael |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=June 16, 2001 |page =L.14}}</ref>
A number of communities in [[Atlantic Canada]], including Bouctouche, [[Moncton]], [[Summerside, Prince Edward Island|Summerside]], [[Caraquet]], [[Clare, Nova Scotia|Clare]] and [[Chéticamp, Nova Scotia|Chéticamp]], hold annual Tintamarres, with the provincial governments of both [[New Brunswick]] and [[Nova Scotia]] promoting these events as tourist attractions.<ref name="Cdn Enc">{{cite web|last=Millette|first=Dominique|title=Tintamarre|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/tintamarre/|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica Dominion Institute]]|accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OlAKTjBc?url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/tintamarre/#|archivedate=2014-04-11|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> The tradition has extended beyond Acadia, with Tintamarres being held to celebrate the [[Franco-Ontarian]] community in [[Hawkesbury, Ontario]],<ref name="Cdn Enc"/> to launch the annual "Semaine de la Francophonie" in [[Toronto]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinkson|first=Kamila|title=Semaine de la Francophonie kicks off in Toronto|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2013/03/20/semaine_de_la_francophonie_kicks_off_in_toronto.html|accessdate=11 April 2014|date=20 March 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OlEfekPA?url=http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2013/03/20/semaine_de_la_francophonie_kicks_off_in_toronto.html#|archivedate=2014-04-11|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> and to mark Acadian Week in the town of [[Saint-Aubin-sur-Mer, Calvados|Saint-Aubin-sur-Mer]], [[Calvados (département)|Calvados]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Grand tintamarre|url=http://www.calvados-tourisme.com/diffusio/fr/sortir/fetes-manifestations/saint-aubin-sur-mer/grand-tintamarre-saint-aubin-sur-mer-sortie-dans-le-calvados-en_TFOFMANOR014V5055KT.php|work=Calvados Tourisme|publisher=Conseil Général du Calvados|accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OlBYImxD?url=http://www.calvados-tourisme.com/diffusio/fr/sortir/fetes-manifestations/saint-aubin-sur-mer/grand-tintamarre-saint-aubin-sur-mer-sortie-dans-le-calvados-en_TFOFMANOR014V5055KT.php#|archivedate=2014-04-11|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> A Tintamarre was held on the [[Saint Leonard – Van Buren Bridge|Saint Leonard – Van Buren International Bridge]] on the [[Canada–United States border]] as part of the [[Acadian World Congress|2014 Acadian World Congress]], which took place in the border counties of [[Aroostook County, Maine|Aroostook]] in Maine, [[Témiscouata Regional County Municipality|Témiscouata]] in Quebec, and [[Victoria County, New Brunswick|Victoria]], [[Madawaska County, New Brunswick|Madawaska]] and [[Restigouche County, New Brunswick|Restigouche]] in New Brunswick.<ref>{{cite news|last=Olmstead|first=Kathryn|title=Van Buren, Canadian towns reach across border to get ready for World Acadian Congress in August|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2014/04/10/living/van-buren-canadian-towns-reach-across-border-to-get-ready-for-world-acadian-congress-in-august/|accessdate=11 April 2014|newspaper=[[Bangor Daily News]]|date=10 April 2014|archiveurl=http://bangordailynews.com/2014/04/10/living/van-buren-canadian-towns-reach-across-border-to-get-ready-for-world-acadian-congress-in-august/|archivedate=11 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Olmstead|first1=Kathryn|title=Moved by the Acadian celebration|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2014/08/14/living/moved-by-the-acadian-celebration/|accessdate=14 August 2014|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|date=14 August 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RpXY0LAG?url=https://bangordailynews.com/2014/08/14/living/moved-by-the-acadian-celebration/#|archivedate=2014-08-14|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> The largest tintamarre parade is actually held in Bouctouche, New Brunswick, while in Caraquet, New Brunswick people gather in the streets to make noise, making more like a “foire” meaning a fair or festival.
